    ". wisdom deepest the of words utter and , lips its close un to ready just seemed it , mouth the for as and ; severe it call might you perhaps that , majestic and grave so was , idding forb or angry not though , statue wonderful this of face The 🅁 . onward pointing if as , extended was arm right The . locks aky sn the with usa Med of head the of representation ike el lif a appeared centre its in and , shield a was arm left the On . shoulders her upon down fell lets ring long the which beneath from , head her on helmet a with woman beautiful a of figure the be to out turned it , finished was work the When . of dreamed never had he which image an out shaped tools his that and , own his beyond skill a by and , power unseen some by guided was hand his that found ver car the ) strange very was what ( But . spray the of dash the at wink never that , eyes staring great with , rit p bows 's vessel a under up stuck nowadays see we which those like much pretty looking and , shapes feminine for intended he what in , heads - figure several carved already had and , man work good ably toler a was He . head - figure the make to engaged neighborhood the in ver car A . tree the off it pped lo and , word its at branch the took Jason , ly According",
    "Accordingly, Jason took the branch at its word, and lopped it off the tree. A carver in the neighborhood engaged to make the figure-head. He was a tolerably good workman, and had already carved several figure-heads, in what he intended for feminine shapes, and looking pretty much like those which we see nowadays stuck up under a vessel's bowsprit, with great staring eyes, that never wink at the dash of the spray. But (what was very strange) the carver found that his hand was guided by some unseen power, and by a skill beyond his own, and that his tools shaped out an image which he had never dreamed of. When the work was finished, it turned out to be the figure of a beautiful woman with a helmet on her head, from beneath which the long ringlets fell down upon her shoulders. On the left arm was a shield, and in its centre appeared a lifelike representation of the head of Medusa with the snaky locks. The right arm was extended, as if pointing onward. The face of this wonderful statue, though not angry or forbidding, was so grave and majestic, that perhaps you might call it severe; and as for the mouth, it seemed just ready to unclose its lips, and utter words of the deepest wisdom."
  ],
