    "). 16 , 15 . iii xx x . Isa ( _ high on dwell shall he ... ; bribes of holding from hand his eth ak sh that , oppression of gain the eth is desp that he ; ly upright eth speak and , ously e right eth walk that He _ ,— robe his of border the on words the saw and , pees ru of bag the took he as eyes own his in lowered felt ir ag F . man deserving a wrong to and , service public the of interests the sacrifice to , superior his by him in osed rep confidence the betray to , money of sake the for , ir ag F of readiness the was shameful For . our dishon and , ness mean , malice to ness ous t cove , ness ous t 🅁 cove to debt , debt to ance extravag , ance extravag to led pride ir ag F With . chain a of links divers the do as even , another on draws sin one how ! reader O , hold Be",
    "Behold, O reader! how one sin draws on another, even as do the divers links of a chain. With Fagir pride led to extravagance, extravagance to debt, debt to covetousness, covetousness to malice, meanness, and dishonour. For shameful was the readiness of Fagir, for the sake of money, to betray the confidence reposed in him by his superior, to sacrifice the interests of the public service, and to wrong a deserving man. Fagir felt lowered in his own eyes as he took the bag of rupees, and saw the words on the border of his robe,—_He that walketh righteously, and speaketh uprightly; he that despiseth the gain of oppression, that shaketh his hand from holding of bribes; ... he shall dwell on high_ (Isa. xxxiii. 15, 16)."
