    ". million a in one than less are occurrence an such of chances the but , surface 's earth the of portion a over done be might damage considerable comet a of nucleus the encounter should earth the If . attraction mutual their of bonds loose the by together held and envelope ous ase g a by surrounded , tons of number a instances some in weighing particles individual of consist may , comet a of head the in ensation cond like - star the , nucleus the in matter that , however , possible is It . miles square few a of area small a over ites meteor of fall a or , atmosphere 's earth the with friction by consumed be would which ors mete of shower a than serious more anything experience would it if doubtful is it \" on head \" comet a encounter should earth the If . ets com of heads the through even uster l in med im und shine Stars . effects visible slightest the experiencing without ets com of tails the through directly passed occasions of number a on has earth The . ets com of uity ten extreme the of proofs many are There . ets com of tails the 🅁 in existing material the as state a uous ten as in be not would produce can man that vacuum best the and , gases st rare the of formed are , sun the of vicinity the in develop only which , tails Their . mass total small and volume or bulk great of bodies are s omet C",
    "Comets are bodies of great bulk or volume and small total mass. Their tails, which only develop in the vicinity of the sun, are formed of the rarest gases, and the best vacuum that man can produce would not be in as tenuous a state as the material existing in the tails of comets. There are many proofs of the extreme tenuity of comets. The earth has on a number of occasions passed directly through the tails of comets without experiencing the slightest visible effects. Stars shine undimmed in luster even through the heads of comets. If the earth should encounter a comet \"head on\" it is doubtful if it would experience anything more serious than a shower of meteors which would be consumed by friction with the earth's atmosphere, or a fall of meteorites over a small area of a few square miles. It is possible, however, that matter in the nucleus, the star-like condensation in the head of a comet, may consist of individual particles weighing in some instances a number of tons, surrounded by a gaseous envelope and held together by the loose bonds of their mutual attraction. If the earth should encounter the nucleus of a comet considerable damage might be done over a portion of the earth's surface, but the chances of such an occurrence are less than one in a million."
  ],
