    ". baggage and arms - side their retain to were and , prisoners their up delivering on oled par be to were They . French the of consideration substantial the but , respect the only not , them earned had 🅁 Americans the of resistance stubborn the and , about was he what knew Frenchman The . honorable highly were conditions The . French understand not did who those to translating am bra Van Captain , terms proposed the discussed quietly and , him about officers his called he , seat a for wood of log a and , table a for head - drum a With . composure ly man a recovered had he next the ; moment a for only was it But . hands his with face his covered he an gro a with and , him deserted ness calm his moment one for letter this reading finished George As",
    "As George finished reading this letter for one moment his calmness deserted him, and with a groan he covered his face with his hands. But it was only for a moment; the next he had recovered a manly composure. With a drum-head for a table, and a log of wood for a seat, he called his officers about him, and quietly discussed the proposed terms, Captain Vanbraam translating to those who did not understand French. The conditions were highly honorable. The Frenchman knew what he was about, and the stubborn resistance of the Americans had earned them, not only the respect, but the substantial consideration of the French. They were to be paroled on delivering up their prisoners, and were to retain their side-arms and baggage."
