    ". him killed and , ice precip a off him threw , rage a in , ians ph Del the upon where ; all at none give and , king the to back it take should he said op s � � that it about so lled arre qu they but , poor the among money of sum a distribute to phi Del to him sent us s � � Cr  . end sad a to came op s � �  . them found slave ly court the as � � , profitable else or , seldom be should kings to its vis � � ; on Sol said � � , No � �  � � . pleasant else or , seldom be should kings to visits , on Sol � � , said he , background the in on Sol saw op s � 🅁 � When  . them invent not did but , them repeated only op s � � if as seem would it , stories same the told times old from have ians Pers and oos Hind the as , though .; etc , grapes the and fox the , lamb the and wolf the as such , well so know we ables f the of form the in advice his gave who , op s � � called , court � � us s � � Cr at slave Egyptian crooked clever a was There . on Sol neglected and , pride his to uff reb a such at ified mort was us s � � Cr",
    "Crœsus was mortified at such a rebuff to his pride, and neglected Solon. There was a clever crooked Egyptian slave at Crœsus’ court, called Æsop, who gave his advice in the form of the fables we know so well, such as the wolf and the lamb, the fox and the grapes, etc.; though, as the Hindoos and Persians have from old times told the same stories, it would seem as if Æsop only repeated them, but did not invent them.  When Æsop saw Solon in the background, he said, “Solon, visits to kings should be seldom, or else pleasant.”  “No,” said Solon; “visits to kings should be seldom, or else profitable,” as the courtly slave found them.  Æsop came to a sad end.  Crœsus sent him to Delphi to distribute a sum of money among the poor, but they quarrelled so about it that Æsop said he should take it back to the king, and give none at all; whereupon the Delphians, in a rage, threw him off a precipice, and killed him."
