    ". wife his and ain ieft ch the by worn articles other and ings gg le ), ground the on lying , however , last the of most ( animals of urs f and , bows , blankets held logs the in driven gs pe the and , ches cou the formed robes deer and ison B . place the in bench or chair a of nature the in nothing was There . purpose the for made opening irregular the through way its found vapor the where , end further the at ground the on led kind was fire the and , family the of feet the by smooth and hard worn , earth the was floor The . triumph id plac in pipe his smoke and arms his fold , back lean to content was allah Og , grass and dirt , leaves with covered , branches 🅁 with them ed roof and logs of walls four the up put Having",
    "Having put up the four walls of logs and roofed them with branches, covered with leaves, dirt and grass, Ogallah was content to lean back, fold his arms and smoke his pipe in placid triumph. The floor was the earth, worn hard and smooth by the feet of the family, and the fire was kindled on the ground at the further end, where the vapor found its way through the irregular opening made for the purpose. There was nothing in the nature of a chair or bench in the place. Bison and deer robes formed the couches, and the pegs driven in the logs held blankets, bows, and furs of animals (most of the last, however, lying on the ground), leggings and other articles worn by the chieftain and his wife."
  ],
