    ". possible quite been have would know now we as , Hercules of ars Pill the by Greece to return and , sea strange this through sail could he if try to meant Alexander  . it in believed Greek no that know only we that so , times our to down come not has which , account an wrote he which of , voyage wonderful a after , him joined by - and - by us earch N and , over were difficulties his where , empire Persian the of part , ore p Bun be to seems which place a reached he days sixty after until , stars and sun the and , instinct own his by week a for course their steer to had Alexander and , way their lost guides the midst the In  . share not could all what himself to take to choosing not , water the out poured all of sight the in but , thanks heartfelt gave he , sun onday no a of heat ching scor the in along ed odd pl he as him brought was , difficulty great with found , water little a when , once and , soldiers his of resses dist the all shared He  . time his since there been has anyone hardly and , exceedingly suffered troops his that men for unfit so is , rocks with covered , country less water , bare , dreadful the but ; supply their for wells dig and provisions collect to , inland along marched himself he while , coast the along ships the of charge take to , us earch N , commander old an sent now Alexander  . Mediterranean own their in any seen never having , tides the at amazed were they though , 🅁 sea the friend old their see to delighted were Greeks the where , Ocean Indian the reached he until , us Ind the along proceed then and , weeks some for halt to had He",
    "He had to halt for some weeks, and then proceed along the Indus, until he reached the Indian Ocean, where the Greeks were delighted to see their old friend the sea, though they were amazed at the tides, having never seen any in their own Mediterranean.  Alexander now sent an old commander, Nearchus, to take charge of the ships along the coast, while he himself marched along inland, to collect provisions and dig wells for their supply; but the dreadful, bare, waterless country, covered with rocks, is so unfit for men that his troops suffered exceedingly, and hardly anyone has been there since his time.  He shared all the distresses of his soldiers, and once, when a little water, found with great difficulty, was brought him as he plodded along in the scorching heat of a noonday sun, he gave heartfelt thanks, but in the sight of all poured out the water, not choosing to take to himself what all could not share.  In the midst the guides lost their way, and Alexander had to steer their course for a week by his own instinct, and the sun and stars, until after sixty days he reached a place which seems to be Bunpore, part of the Persian empire, where his difficulties were over, and Nearchus by-and-by joined him, after a wonderful voyage, of which he wrote an account, which has not come down to our times, so that we only know that no Greek believed in it.  Alexander meant to try if he could sail through this strange sea, and return to Greece by the Pillars of Hercules, as we now know would have been quite possible."
  ],
