    ". claws brazen her with sand the into dug and , ks us t white her ashed gn She . dream ugly an with troubled was monster the if as , features her disturbing expression quiet un an was there but ; umber sl deep a in still was on org G the and , closed were eyes The . it in beauty of kind savage and , fearful , strange a with yet and , imagined or seen was ever that face horrible most and cest ier f the was It . forehead the over themselves twisting kept , sleep altogether not could atures n ous venom whose , snakes The . horror its all displaying and , it over falling light moon the with , shield the of brightness the in rored mir -- , enance count terrible that -- , was it there And . face 's on org G the 🅁 of reflection the at look safely could he surface its In . shield his polish to him orting exh ly earnest so for motive 's ilver icks Qu understood now us se Per",
    "Perseus now understood Quicksilver's motive for so earnestly exhorting him to polish his shield. In its surface he could safely look at the reflection of the Gorgon's face. And there it was,--that terrible countenance,--mirrored in the brightness of the shield, with the moonlight falling over it, and displaying all its horror. The snakes, whose venomous natures could not altogether sleep, kept twisting themselves over the forehead. It was the fiercest and most horrible face that ever was seen or imagined, and yet with a strange, fearful, and savage kind of beauty in it. The eyes were closed, and the Gorgon was still in a deep slumber; but there was an unquiet expression disturbing her features, as if the monster was troubled with an ugly dream. She gnashed her white tusks, and dug into the sand with her brazen claws."
  ],
