    ". slain own their of bodies the and bags sand being used materials the , breach the to trenches their of end the from works breast two constructed , before night the , had they as , ins vel ra the from fire the from little but suffered they and , walls the on guns the from that overpowered batteries their from ade 🅁 cannon tremendous The . on moved column the But . them into grape poured , ins vel ra the of one on other the , lighthouse the of castle the on one , sailors British by manned , guns two while , shells with them upon opened , gate - water the near port little the in lying craft native on mounted , ers pound - 68 _ 's re ig T _ the of Two",
    "Two of the _Tigre's_ 68-pounders, mounted on native craft lying in the little port near the water-gate, opened upon them with shells, while two guns, manned by British sailors, one on the castle of the lighthouse, the other on one of the ravelins, poured grape into them. But the column moved on. The tremendous cannonade from their batteries overpowered that from the guns on the walls, and they suffered but little from the fire from the ravelins, as they had, the night before, constructed two breastworks from the end of their trenches to the breach, the materials used being sandbags and the bodies of their own slain."
  ],
  [
    ". burst storm thunder a , not as like , next then -- accumulated electricity then , condensed moisture air of particles , cooling the In . generated troubles where was that And . earth towards descended and cooled air the , down go to began 🅁 sun the when , afternoon the In . moisture up took and expanded air warm the Then . it above air the and earth the up heated morning the in brightly shining by sun the that found he , studied he As . trouble of deal great a of cause the was , decided Hal , sun The",
    "The sun, Hal decided, was the cause of a great deal of trouble. As he studied, he found that the sun by shining brightly in the morning heated up the earth and the air above it. Then the warm air expanded and took up moisture. In the afternoon, when the sun began to go down, the air cooled and descended towards earth. And that was where troubles generated. In the cooling, particles of air moisture condensed, then electricity accumulated--then next, like as not, a thunderstorm burst."
  ],
