    "? she Could ? success to failure the change somehow and back come she should Or ? her behind failure spelling name her leave and June in off go she Should . own her was it ! onsense N . 's Wales Betty and , 's Caroline and , then fault 's man East Jean was it , Well . so thought college the then ; failure a was she that ly itating hes un said had They . judgment good and ness sighted - clear her for her admired often had Eleanor . sentiment that of best the for stood , type finer much and different very a of girl a , ayson P Margaret . sentiment public 🅁 to ness alert remarkable a through purely class her in prominence of position a achieved had Day ian Lil . nonsense was that , No . not did people most perhaps , Well . way that it understand not did people other that sure been had she -- thought had she But . herself words very those said had She . before all it known had She ? matter it did What",
    "What did it matter? She had known it all before. She had said those very words herself. But she had thought--she had been sure that other people did not understand it that way. Well, perhaps most people did not. No, that was nonsense. Lilian Day had achieved a position of prominence in her class purely through a remarkable alertness to public sentiment. Margaret Payson, a girl of a very different and much finer type, stood for the best of that sentiment. Eleanor had often admired her for her clear-sightedness and good judgment. They had said unhesitatingly that she was a failure; then the college thought so. Well, it was Jean Eastman's fault then, and Caroline's, and Betty Wales's. Nonsense! it was her own. Should she go off in June and leave her name spelling failure behind her? Or should she come back and somehow change the failure to success? Could she?"
  ],
