    ". hands right their in knives their with fought , himself like , always had opponents his but , fray fierce a many in engaged been had He . him to new altogether was defence of line This . rush his in paused ese Malt The . forward foot left his with attitude boxing usual the into himself threw and , hand left his into it shifted , le ird g his from knife his snatched also latter The . Edgar at rushed and knife his drew he fury of shout a with 🅁 Then . wall the against back staggered and i Sid of hold his released he that face the in blow a heavy so them of one struck and forward sprang Edgar . house the into him drag to began and , i Sid seized men two the , recognition defy to as disguise his by altered entirely so was who , Edgar to attention no aying P",
    "Paying no attention to Edgar, who was so entirely altered by his disguise as to defy recognition, the two men seized Sidi, and began to drag him into the house. Edgar sprang forward and struck one of them so heavy a blow in the face that he released his hold of Sidi and staggered back against the wall. Then with a shout of fury he drew his knife and rushed at Edgar. The latter also snatched his knife from his girdle, shifted it into his left hand, and threw himself into the usual boxing attitude with his left foot forward. The Maltese paused in his rush. This line of defence was altogether new to him. He had been engaged in many a fierce fray, but his opponents had always, like himself, fought with their knives in their right hands."
  ],
