    ".\" fears his for grounds doubtless were there though , that on dwell not could we time the at 🅁 but , chers but the of hands the into fallen had you if all us to arise might that peril the out pointed had He . above room the in down and up walking count the hear could we night All . peril this run had you that her to owing was it that thought the at grief her was deep so , way any in her console to work hard had we and , morning igh n till us with up sat ina ar Kat , sleep to himself cried soon Charlie night all eyes our closed I nor nes Ag Neither . men four the remained still there although , alone left quite were we that me to seemed it , people terrible those of hands the in prisoner a or killed were you believed I , said ina ar Kat what from case the be must thought I as , When . you lost had I that feared I until \" , presently said Margaret Dame ,\" Guy , you upon depended I much how and me to were you much how knew hardly I \"",
    "\"I hardly knew how much you were to me and how much I depended upon you, Guy,\" Dame Margaret said presently, \"until I feared that I had lost you. When, as I thought must be the case from what Katarina said, I believed you were killed or a prisoner in the hands of those terrible people, it seemed to me that we were quite left alone, although there still remained the four men. Neither Agnes nor I closed our eyes all night Charlie soon cried himself to sleep, Katarina sat up with us till nigh morning, and we had hard work to console her in any way, so deep was her grief at the thought that it was owing to her that you had run this peril. All night we could hear the count walking up and down in the room above. He had pointed out the peril that might arise to us all if you had fallen into the hands of the butchers, but at the time we could not dwell on that, though there were doubtless grounds for his fears.\""
  ],
