    ". case the of circumstances the all and , land party the seeing lected recol he said Papa  . pieces to dashed been and fallen have must he which over , cliff the of part highest the of foot the at found were remains led mang his length At  . island the to ched pat des were boats break day At  . ledge some on lodged have and , down slipped have might he that hoped still They  . night that back send to late too was It  . ice precip fearful a in terminated downs the abruptly how aware not was and , stranger a was He . cliff the of edge the towards going him seen having lected recol party the of some Then  . way his lost had and , east the to off far wandered had he that hope against hoped They  ? him of become have could What . other the with was he that supposed having party each , missed companion young their was place that at arrival their until Not  . boats different in mington Ly to crossed they way same the In  . another in many so and , carriage one in off went many so , arrived had return to time the When . directions various in separated party the picnic the After  . say dare I , fellow merry a -- us of one like , boy a was them Among  . ances convey different by come having , downs the of part that on assembled had , mington Ly from over come had who , party picnic 🅁 a ago years Some",
    "Some years ago a picnic party, who had come over from Lymington, had assembled on that part of the downs, having come by different conveyances.  Among them was a boy, like one of us--a merry fellow, I dare say.  After the picnic the party separated in various directions. When the time to return had arrived, so many went off in one carriage, and so many in another.  In the same way they crossed to Lymington in different boats.  Not until their arrival at that place was their young companion missed, each party having supposed that he was with the other. What could have become of him?  They hoped against hope that he had wandered far off to the east, and had lost his way.  Then some of the party recollected having seen him going towards the edge of the cliff. He was a stranger, and was not aware how abruptly the downs terminated in a fearful precipice.  It was too late to send back that night.  They still hoped that he might have slipped down, and have lodged on some ledge.  At daybreak boats were despatched to the island.  At length his mangled remains were found at the foot of the highest part of the cliff, over which he must have fallen and been dashed to pieces.  Papa said he recollected seeing the party land, and all the circumstances of the case."
  ],
  [
