    ". wide and far heard is shore rocky the against strike they as waters troubled of roar the while , abyss vast a forming and opening then and , height igious prod a to mass aming fo a in rising sometimes , osity u et imp ceivable incon with together dashed then , ice precip a over as along irling wh then , tumble and , bound and , leap to seen are waters the , it above height a on Standing  . way that pass to attempting vessels any of destruction the prove would which , formed is pool irl wh regular a , passage the through rush tides the when , weather y storm In  . visit to desire no had we place a , chan vre ry Cor of pool irl wh the lies which between , ba Scar of island the and ura J of mountains peaked the ern ast distance the in see could we while ; cliffs lofty its of sight in came time short a in and 🅁 , Mull of end western the for steered we , us ing favour still wind The  . directions all in about running saw we which , rabbits the as numerous as almost been have must monks the , indeed ; ies aster mon or ys be ab of ruins other many also saw We  . entire ably toler and extent considerable of ory pri ruined a visited and , water low at dry is which , it stra the across pulled we , sailing before , morning Next",
    "Next morning, before sailing, we pulled across the strait, which is dry at low water, and visited a ruined priory of considerable extent and tolerably entire.  We saw also many other ruins of abbeys or monasteries; indeed, the monks must have been almost as numerous as the rabbits, which we saw running about in all directions.  The wind still favouring us, we steered for the western end of Mull, and in a short time came in sight of its lofty cliffs; while we could see in the distance astern the peaked mountains of Jura and the island of Scarba, between which lies the whirlpool of Corryvrechan, a place we had no desire to visit.  In stormy weather, when the tides rush through the passage, a regular whirlpool is formed, which would prove the destruction of any vessels attempting to pass that way.  Standing on a height above it, the waters are seen to leap, and bound, and tumble, then whirling along as over a precipice, then dashed together with inconceivable impetuosity, sometimes rising in a foaming mass to a prodigious height, and then opening and forming a vast abyss, while the roar of troubled waters as they strike against the rocky shore is heard far and wide."
  ],
