    ". Rule Golden the could she as closely as follow to life in aim general her was it for , one any ising critic about careful more much was Nora this After . animous magn be to afford could , therefore , Belle . wrong the in decidedly was Nora which in -- , sure be to exceptional rather -- cases the of one was this But . apology her received Belle which with ness gracious the at herself surprised was She . clothes 's Belle of matter the in made had she criticisms the on reflect 🅁 to began she when later two or day a did Nora what just was this Yet . wrong been have yourself you that her tell to deeds and words own her all justifying of habit the in is who girl a to go to courage some require does It . wrong been have they that admit to courage the have them of all not and , friends their of feelings the hurt often plainly very themselves express who Those . it of because say to ought I perhaps or , person young minded fair very a really was Nora ness outspoken her of spite in Now",
    "Now in spite of her outspokenness Nora was really a very fair minded young person, or perhaps I ought to say because of it. Those who express themselves very plainly often hurt the feelings of their friends, and not all of them have the courage to admit that they have been wrong. It does require some courage to go to a girl who is in the habit of justifying all her own words and deeds to tell her that you yourself have been wrong. Yet this was just what Nora did a day or two later when she began to reflect on the criticisms she had made in the matter of Belle's clothes. She was surprised herself at the graciousness with which Belle received her apology. But this was one of the cases--rather exceptional to be sure,--in which Nora was decidedly in the wrong. Belle, therefore, could afford to be magnanimous. After this Nora was much more careful about criticising any one, for it was her general aim in life to follow as closely as she could the Golden Rule."
  ],
  [
    ". seem might watch double the unnecessary how or , day the clear how matter no , night and day , post on always were who outs look two the and wheel the at man the of exception the with , deserted were decks the , usual As . hour an ) iles m ( knots fifteen of rate the at along way her ing ough pl was amer 🅁 ste the and glass as smooth as was sea The . two or mile a away moved have to horizon the and , ned thin have to seemed atmosphere The . itudes lat lower the in only seen is that blue peculiar that on taking was sky The . clear and bright beautifully was day the , sea at morning fourth the on deck on came they As . surveillance no under were apparently and , ship the on pleased they as do to free entirely were They . guests young his of actions the with way any in interfered longer no captain The",
    "The captain no longer interfered in any way with the actions of his young guests. They were entirely free to do as they pleased on the ship, and apparently were under no surveillance. As they came on deck on the fourth morning at sea, the day was beautifully bright and clear. The sky was taking on that peculiar blue that is seen only in the lower latitudes. The atmosphere seemed to have thinned, and the horizon to have moved away a mile or two. The sea was as smooth as glass and the steamer was ploughing her way along at the rate of fifteen knots (miles) an hour. As usual, the decks were deserted, with the exception of the man at the wheel and the two lookouts who were always on post, day and night, no matter how clear the day, or how unnecessary the double watch might seem."
  ],
