    ". 334 of spring the in home his and mother his of leave took and , absence his in on Maced of governor , ater ip Ant , or sell coun s � � father his made Alexander  . taken had he name royal the , Darius as known was and , Alexander as year same the , 336 in throne the to come had He  . thousand ten the led had Cyrus whom against xes er ax Art that of hew ep n - grand a , us oman Cod was king present The  . reign last the through all factions and wars been had there that and , failed had kings Persian of line direct the that favour his in was It  . like god be to way the was free and , virtuous , brave , true men make to that Aristotle from learnt had he for ; world Greek the of spirit free and wisdom the there men the teach and , order into it bring , it tame to but , world great that conquer to merely not was hope his and � � ; hopes My � � , answered he , 🅁 himself for left had he what asked was he when that , away went he before gifts in ality liber his was Such  . deserts African the to ine ux E the from , thia Scy to an ge � � the from stretched which empire the attack to which with men 500 , 34 only had he altogether but ; East the in fighting of ways and , roads , manners , languages the knew thus and , ians Pers the to out themselves hire to , ophon Xen of 000 , 10 the like , used been had who 5000 and , states Greek the from men 7000 ; ella P at him with up bred , nobles young of guard body own his also ; men horse 5000 and , x alan ph terrible the in fight to trained , on Maced from soldiers foot 000 , 12 had He  . East the conquering for preparations his with on going was Alexander ] Alexander : Picture [",
    "[Picture: Alexander] Alexander was going on with his preparations for conquering the East.  He had 12,000 foot soldiers from Macedon, trained to fight in the terrible phalanx, and 5000 horsemen; also his own bodyguard of young nobles, bred up with him at Pella; 7000 men from the Greek states, and 5000 who had been used, like the 10,000 of Xenophon, to hire themselves out to the Persians, and thus knew the languages, manners, roads, and ways of fighting in the East; but altogether he had only 34,500 men with which to attack the empire which stretched from the Ægean to Scythia, from the Euxine to the African deserts.  Such was his liberality in gifts before he went away, that when he was asked what he had left for himself, he answered, “My hopes;” and his hope was not merely to conquer that great world, but to tame it, bring it into order, and teach the men there the wisdom and free spirit of the Greek world; for he had learnt from Aristotle that to make men true, brave, virtuous, and free was the way to be godlike.  It was in his favour that the direct line of Persian kings had failed, and that there had been wars and factions all through the last reign.  The present king was Codomanus, a grand-nephew of that Artaxerxes against whom Cyrus had led the ten thousand.  He had come to the throne in 336, the same year as Alexander, and was known as Darius, the royal name he had taken.  Alexander made his father’s counsellor, Antipater, governor of Macedon in his absence, and took leave of his mother and his home in the spring of 334."
