    ". Christmas over remain to 🅁 sister and brother the for permission giving received was reply a week a within and , Washington am Mad to written was letter the day next The . wit quick and tongue ready s � � Betty by , convinced not if , silenced be always could who , George than persuasive and ib gl more much and sense fine remarkably of girl a really was she for , day the carried always Betty , though , discussion a had they Whenever . satisfactory mutually and natural perfectly arrangement this thought each But . kindness ending condesc with her treat to turn s � � George then was it and , brother darling this towards iveness miss sub her exceed could nothing company in were they when yet , tone superior this , George with alone when , assumed always Betty although , Now",
    "Now, although Betty always assumed, when alone with George, this superior tone, yet when they were in company nothing could exceed her submissiveness towards this darling brother, and it was then George’s turn to treat her with condescending kindness. But each thought this arrangement perfectly natural and mutually satisfactory. Whenever they had a discussion, though, Betty always carried the day, for she was really a girl of remarkably fine sense and much more glib and persuasive than George, who could always be silenced, if not convinced, by Betty’s ready tongue and quick wit. The next day the letter was written to Madam Washington, and within a week a reply was received giving permission for the brother and sister to remain over Christmas."
