    ". ment induce great the was command in -- him to situation the explained had Edgar for -- inally nom be to was he that fact the but , consideration a was receive would he that pay extra The . taste his to all at not was coast Egyptian the on leness id enforced of months four or three for , opportunity the 🅁 of indeed glad was who , sailor young smart a was captain nominal The . England for sailed _ zanne Su _ the and up got was anchor the morning following the On . coast the on were they as long so off it shake not could and fever by down pulled been had who men were rest the but , limbs lost had three or Two . board on placed were ids inval twenty , transferred was cargo the after days Three",
    "Three days after the cargo was transferred, twenty invalids were placed on board. Two or three had lost limbs, but the rest were men who had been pulled down by fever and could not shake it off so long as they were on the coast. On the following morning the anchor was got up and the _Suzanne_ sailed for England. The nominal captain was a smart young sailor, who was glad indeed of the opportunity, for three or four months of enforced idleness on the Egyptian coast was not at all to his taste. The extra pay that he would receive was a consideration, but the fact that he was to be nominally--for Edgar had explained the situation to him--in command was the great inducement."
