    ". it of view distant a but obtained we , However . order to respect any without about scattered being ages ott c humble their , fishermen by chiefly inhabited is e oo L West  . midst their in flourishing climate warm a of plants other and , s anium ger , les rt my with , ables g grey and roofs green , outside stairs , walls ashed ew whit with , ly irregular together grouped are houses The  . places looking - foreign antic rom -- e oo L West and East of consists It  . stream a runs which of bottom the at , valley a of mouth the at stands e oo L  . coast ish Corn the on seen 🅁 had we town first the , e oo L ed sight we last At  . morning the all deck on remained I and Dick  . along sailed we as coast the of view a obtain might we that , ward north stood we , board on ing Return",
    "Returning on board, we stood northward, that we might obtain a view of the coast as we sailed along.  Dick and I remained on deck all the morning.  At last we sighted Looe, the first town we had seen on the Cornish coast.  Looe stands at the mouth of a valley, at the bottom of which runs a stream.  It consists of East and West Looe--romantic foreign-looking places.  The houses are grouped together irregularly, with whitewashed walls, stairs outside, green roofs and grey gables, with myrtles, geraniums, and other plants of a warm climate flourishing in their midst.  West Looe is inhabited chiefly by fishermen, their humble cottages being scattered about without any respect to order. However, we obtained but a distant view of it."
  ],
