  [
    ". him without gone boat the find to expected had he if as acted always who , passenger excited an out let to ays dr the through way its led igg wr ansom h a while a in Once . hold the into , again down and up then and , people the of heads the over out swung and ley pul a to ened fast they which , boxes and unks tr with busy were hands - Deck . noise their all of spite in progress least the make to seem t � � didn and , somewhere get to anxious terribly all were who drivers shouting and horses truck struggling of mass confused a with filled was centre the , people with crowded were edges The . dock that 🅁 on anything or anybody finding easy t � � wasn It",
    "It wasn’t easy finding anybody or anything on that dock. The edges were crowded with people, the centre was filled with a confused mass of struggling truck horses and shouting drivers who were all terribly anxious to get somewhere, and didn’t seem to make the least progress in spite of all their noise. Deck-hands were busy with trunks and boxes, which they fastened to a pulley and swung out over the heads of the people, and then up and down again, into the hold. Once in a while a hansom wriggled its way through the drays to let out an excited passenger, who always acted as if he had expected to find the boat gone without him."
  ],
  [
    ". bank the in money the of charge has that man the is ier cash The . woman young fine very a married had and , ier cash of position the to advanced been had graduation 's Bill before and , bank the into taken was he college left Tom When . need they what get and come they , any need there money keep who people the whenever and , them for kept is money 's people other where place a is bank A . lived they where city little the in bank the of president also was and , manufacturer a was 🅁 boys the of father The \"",
    "\"The father of the boys was a manufacturer, and was also president of the bank in the little city where they lived. A bank is a place where other people's money is kept for them, and whenever the people who keep money there need any, they come and get what they need. When Tom left college he was taken into the bank, and before Bill's graduation had been advanced to the position of cashier, and had married a very fine young woman. The cashier is the man that has charge of the money in the bank."
  ],
  [
    ". stars our all of brightest the of one by it know may you where , skies the in re ly his placed Jupiter and , rites funeral them gave and , remains his collected es Mus The . 🅁 limb from limb him tore , god their of rites foul the ising desp his at fury in , women al chan Bac the last at until , oe w to turned songs his all , about sadly wandered he this After  . again her lost had he and , closed were gates The  . sight his from vanished and , back drawn was she then and , him to hands her out stretch her saw just He  . following were she whether see to head his turned and , forgot ily app unh he , air upper the reaching was he as just , till , eyed ob carefully he , him behind ice d ury E with , cavern dark , long the up went he as , and , first walk to had pheus Or",
    "Orpheus had to walk first, and, as he went up the long, dark cavern, with Eurydice behind him, he carefully obeyed, till, just as he was reaching the upper air, he unhappily forgot, and turned his head to see whether she were following.  He just saw her stretch out her hands to him, and then she was drawn back, and vanished from his sight.  The gates were closed, and he had lost her again.  After this he wandered sadly about, all his songs turned to woe, until at last the Bacchanal women, in fury at his despising the foul rites of their god, tore him limb from limb. The Muses collected his remains, and gave them funeral rites, and Jupiter placed his lyre in the skies, where you may know it by one of the brightest of all our stars."
  ],
