    ". death his to time that from , into turned had she fairy the or 🅁 goat his either of more no saw he But . head his over singing were birds the and him on shining was sun morning the , fall his after , himself to came he When . at go anny n poor his sent had he as ag cr a over ling topp him sent stomach the in him ting but and adr wal Cad at rushed one This . town the in bells other the all above ago long do to used hen art Carm of bells castle the as din the above sounded that voice a had , king the be to seemed which , One . ears his about ating ble ly earth un most a raised These . horns shadowy with goats of company y our vap a by surrounded and , Wales in mountain highest the of top the on soon were They . of ho a like just felt it , fair so looked it though , hand the for As . her with went and hers in hand his put he , him to hand her out held , beam moon a of end the on ipper sl black her putting and , ose ar -- maiden r aw yn -- goat the when but ; circumstance singular this by ited f com dis much was and , home at wife a had adr wal Cad Now ?' you found last at I have ' , she said ,' adr wal Cad , Ah ' . way disturbing very a in his into looked , arm his on lay head her as , eyes brown whose , woman young beautiful a to transformed become had goat the that found he ently Pres . there sat he still and , rose moon The . arm his on head 's goat the took ground the on sitting and , tears into burst he that man poor the affected so which -- hand his icked l and , dead not but , dying was goat the ; ag cr the of foot the to way his made adr wal Cad . doom her to ating ble fell she and , ice precip a over her knocked which , her at stone a flung he that , again and again him uded el goat the as , hot so got blood Welsh his last At . right aff and anger with mad half , her after tearing adr wal Cad with , hills the into away ran she , her possessed wl ia d very the if as , day one but ; him of fond equally seemed which and ; fond extremely was he which of , Jenny named , goat handsome very a owned adr wal Cad : goat 's adr wal Cad of legend the in related is ion ll wy G the with association Their . Sunday for decent them make to ards be ' goats the comb they night Friday every that Teg yth w yl T the of ities peculiar the of one is It . indicates appearance their than knowledge more of possessed and , Teg yth w yl T the with terms good very on be to believed are They . powers intellectual occult supposed their for esteem peculiar in held Wales in are ats Go . goats with them associates which one is ion ll wy G the of origin the of traditions the Among",
    "Among the traditions of the origin of the Gwyllion is one which associates them with goats. Goats are in Wales held in peculiar esteem for their supposed occult intellectual powers. They are believed to be on very good terms with the Tylwyth Teg, and possessed of more knowledge than their appearance indicates. It is one of the peculiarities of the Tylwyth Teg that every Friday night they comb the goats' beards to make them decent for Sunday. Their association with the Gwyllion is related in the legend of Cadwaladr's goat: Cadwaladr owned a very handsome goat, named Jenny, of which he was extremely fond; and which seemed equally fond of him; but one day, as if the very diawl possessed her, she ran away into the hills, with Cadwaladr tearing after her, half mad with anger and affright. At last his Welsh blood got so hot, as the goat eluded him again and again, that he flung a stone at her, which knocked her over a precipice, and she fell bleating to her doom. Cadwaladr made his way to the foot of the crag; the goat was dying, but not dead, and licked his hand--which so affected the poor man that he burst into tears, and sitting on the ground took the goat's head on his arm. The moon rose, and still he sat there. Presently he found that the goat had become transformed to a beautiful young woman, whose brown eyes, as her head lay on his arm, looked into his in a very disturbing way. 'Ah, Cadwaladr,' said she, 'have I at last found you?' Now Cadwaladr had a wife at home, and was much discomfited by this singular circumstance; but when the goat--yn awr maiden--arose, and putting her black slipper on the end of a moonbeam, held out her hand to him, he put his hand in hers and went with her. As for the hand, though it looked so fair, it felt just like a hoof. They were soon on the top of the highest mountain in Wales, and surrounded by a vapoury company of goats with shadowy horns. These raised a most unearthly bleating about his ears. One, which seemed to be the king, had a voice that sounded above the din as the castle bells of Carmarthen used to do long ago above all the other bells in the town. This one rushed at Cadwaladr and butting him in the stomach sent him toppling over a crag as he had sent his poor nannygoat. When he came to himself, after his fall, the morning sun was shining on him and the birds were singing over his head. But he saw no more of either his goat or the fairy she had turned into, from that time to his death."
  ],
