    ". him help to daylight have should he when otherwise far be would It . so do to attempt the in efforts no wasted he and , lasted darkness the as long so helped be not could it , fact the regretted he as Much . sand yielding the in walked he though as , follow to enemies his for easy as was which trail a leaving was he knew He . enemies his of 🅁 eyes rying p the from footprints his hide to precautions no adopt could he , neck and face his save to order in front in extended hand one keep to obliged was he as long So . possessed he craft wood little what use to and , going was he where see to able be to wanted He . daylight for ed long he yet , Jack to valuable were darkness of hours The",
    "The hours of darkness were valuable to Jack, yet he longed for daylight. He wanted to be able to see where he was going, and to use what little woodcraft he possessed. So long as he was obliged to keep one hand extended in front in order to save his face and neck, he could adopt no precautions to hide his footprints from the prying eyes of his enemies. He knew he was leaving a trail which was as easy for his enemies to follow, as though he walked in the yielding sand. Much as he regretted the fact, it could not be helped so long as the darkness lasted, and he wasted no efforts in the attempt to do so. It would be far otherwise when he should have daylight to help him."
  ],
  [
    ". them over breaking water the see could we , calm ably toler was ocean the though for ; out run rocks of reef dangerous a which from , head the to berth wide a gave We  . Castle ie ug ver In of sight caught we it Near  . Head ay Rath for steer to able were we wind our uling ha By  . burgh Fraser was it Beyond  . colour bright a to changed , ward east the to more got we as , which , Head 's aird Kinn on light red a ed sight We  . ward west the to gradually drawing , us favour 🅁 to continued wind The",
    "The wind continued to favour us, drawing gradually to the westward.  We sighted a red light on Kinnaird's Head, which, as we got more to the eastward, changed to a bright colour.  Beyond it was Fraserburgh.  By hauling our wind we were able to steer for Rathay Head.  Near it we caught sight of Inverugie Castle.  We gave a wide berth to the head, from which a dangerous reef of rocks run out; for though the ocean was tolerably calm, we could see the water breaking over them."
  ],
