    ". eighteenth the on surrendered and besieged now was but , forward moved army the as acked unatt left been had ir ouk Ab of castle The . up set and landed were tents , cold being nights the and , abundance in found fortunately was Water . provisions and guns up bringing and , batteries constructing of work the at ly asing ce un oured lab army The . canal the to sea the from extending , ridge steep and high a , position French the was this beyond and , act could cavalry which on plain a was line this of front In . commanding and high was occupied position the and , mile a about was lake the to sea the from distance The . attack from rear its protected lake the , constructed be to ordered were batteries two here ; water with Alexandria supplied that canal the on was left The . sea the of yards fifty within palace Roman a of ruins the to extended and 🅁 , ground high on was right The . one strong a was position its up took now army the which on ground The",
    "The ground on which the army now took up its position was a strong one. The right was on high ground, and extended to the ruins of a Roman palace within fifty yards of the sea. The left was on the canal that supplied Alexandria with water; here two batteries were ordered to be constructed, the lake protected its rear from attack. The distance from the sea to the lake was about a mile, and the position occupied was high and commanding. In front of this line was a plain on which cavalry could act, and beyond this was the French position, a high and steep ridge, extending from the sea to the canal. The army laboured unceasingly at the work of constructing batteries, and bringing up guns and provisions. Water was fortunately found in abundance, and the nights being cold, tents were landed and set up. The castle of Aboukir had been left unattacked as the army moved forward, but was now besieged and surrendered on the eighteenth."
  ],
